{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5517","authors":[{"fullname":"Bill McGrath","id":"19"}],"title":"An Overview of the Term Frisbee and Its Translations","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:16:34 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:16:34 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p>Although the term \"Frisbee\" is technically a registered trademark of the Wham-O toy company, it is used more popularly than the proper term, \"flying disc.\"\u00a0 In fact, the term \"flying disc\" is rarely used, if ever, often abbreviated to just \"disc.\"\u00a0 Frisbees can be used in a variety of settings, from recreational throwing, to Frisbee golf, to Ultimate Frisbee.<\/p><p>The Chinese term, \"fei pan,\" literally means \"flying plate,\" \"flying dish,\" or \"flying disc\" (\"pan\" is a relatively diverse term in Chinese).\u00a0 The pronunciation of the word \"fei pan\" is not too far from the English term \"Frisbee,\" making it an attractive translation.<\/p><p>The Tibetan term, \"phur sder,\" taken from Khenpo Ts\u00fcltrim Lodr\u00f6's Tibetan-Chinese-English Dictionary of Modern Vocabulary, is a direct calque of the Chinese \"fei pan,\" but the attractive pronounciation and, I would argue, even the meaning of the word is skewed.\u00a0 When \"fei pan\" becomes \"phur sder,\" we no longer have a flying disc, but merely a \"flying plate.\"\u00a0 Therefore, in the vein of the Tibetan translation for airplane, \"gnam grus\" (literally, sky boat; not a calque of the Chinese term \"fei ji,\" flying machine), I have provided an alternative term, \"nam 'khor\" (sky disc) which, I think, is a much more accurate and appropriate translation.<\/p>","title":"An Overview of the Term Frisbee and Its Translations"}]}
